  "title": "Automation as Team Player",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c08265ef124fc6fd",
      "text": "The challenges associated with making automation a 'team player' in a joint human-agent activity are discussed. Joint activity is defined as an extended set of actions that are carried out by an ensemble of people coordinating with each other. To carry out joint activity, each party effectively enters into a Basic Compact, an agreement to facilitate coordination, work toward shared goals, and prevent breakdowns in team coordination. Effective coordination requires establishing and maintaining common ground and an intelligent agent must fulfil the requirements of a Basic Compact to engage in common-grounding activities. [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/3454232_Ten_Challenges_for_Making_Automation_a_Team_Player_in_Joint_Human-Agent_Activity researchgate]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5474ef4887705883",
      "text": "[[Jeff Miller]] provided us with this summary circulating within his community."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1f27251a2d02f30d",
      "text": "Woods, Hoffman, et al., Intelligent Systems, IEEE - December 2004\nUploaded with enhancements requested by David D. Woods 22 August 2013\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "56615d37566b6de3",
      "text": "• A BASIC COMPACT. To be a team player, an intelligent agent must fulfill the\nrequirements of a basic compact to engage in common-grounding activities. (and\nlet other team members know if it can't fully contribute)\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a75977eb4edd4a67",
      "text": "• ADEQUATE MODELS. [TBaTP], model other participants' intentions and actions -\nare they having trouble? are they doing OK? are they blocked? how are others\nresponding to any disruptions\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9d5eb9bbd5bf30cb",
      "text": "• PREDICTABILITY. Human-agent team members must be mutually predictable.\nCurrently, agents taking the initiative to adapt to humans may cause humans to\nhold back, fearing that the agent may jump to a bad conclusion. Therefore make\nthe adaptations obvious and simple to avoid human confusion and reluctance.\nAdaptability and predictability are in tension.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a043ee54e2604a84",
      "text": "• DIRECTABILITY. Agents must be directable. Policies are a way of expressing\ncurrent limits, and being able to change limits without having to change\nagents' code explicitly.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "933103eaafad4dbd",
      "text": "• REVEALING STATUS AND INTENTIONS. Agents must be able to make these obvious.\nExamples of trouble in this area come from jet aircraft systems. Design agents\nto be transparent.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "14d07dc16173bb1f",
      "text": "• INTERPRETING SIGNALS. Agents must be able to interpret signals and form\nmodels of their teammates. (Example is subtext from tone and pauses in spoken\ncommunication.)\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b83412300a2cd132",
      "text": "• GOAL NEGOTIATION. Agents should be able to represent, reason about, and\nmodify their goals in order to coordinate effectively as team members.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f4542ec45158d358",
      "text": "• COLLABORATION. To facilitate give-and-take, agents' understanding, problem\nsolving, and task execution must be incremental and subject to negotiation.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "153f0c3c141b7278",
      "text": "• ATTENTION MANAGEMENT. When does an agent need to be a squeaky wheel, and\nwhen should it keep the channel clear for urgent communication? Airplane\ncockpit automation used as an example of being too quiet.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "14f4df425cdf9a15",
      "text": "• COST CONTROL. Costs of coordination should be kept in mind. Mutual\npredictability and common understanding and purpose help reduce this cost\n"
    },
